<h3><a id="execs" name="execs"></a>4.
Exercises</h3>

<blockquote> <a id="ex1" name="ex1"></a>Create
a directory named <span style="font-weight: bold;">project4</span>
under your web server's document root directory on your hard drive.
Place all HTML files and PHP scripts for this project in this new
directory. <br />

  <br />

  <span style="font-weight: bold;">Note:</span>
If you are working on an MATC lab computer, always save a copy of this
directory and all the files in it to either the class server, a USB
thumb drive, a floppy disk or similar media, at the end of each work
session. Otherwise your work will be lost!
  
  <h4>Exercise 1</h4>

  
  <blockquote>
    
    <p>Download the project zip file containing PHP code for simple user authentication<span style="font-weight: bold;"></span>.</p>

    
    <ol>

      <li><span style="font-weight: bold;"></span>Download and unzip the
<a href="project4.zip">project4.zip</a> file
from the Blackboard version of this document. Note that it contains
"inc", "lib" and "sql" subdirectories. You should copy all files and
directories to your <span style="font-weight: bold;">project 4</span> directory. </li>

      <li><span style="font-weight: bold;"></span>Modify
the <span style="font-weight: bold;">config.inc.php</span>
file in the "inc" directory to contain the class server name (itmysql.matcmadison.edu), your MySQL
username, password and personal database name (same as your username). <br />

      </li>

      <li>Execute the <span style="font-weight: bold;">structure.sql</span>
script in the "sql" directory to create the tables used by the PHP scripts <span style="font-weight: bold;"></span>
in your personal database on the class server. Note that a test user is inserted in the <span style="font-weight: bold;">users</span> table.<br />

      </li>

      <li>Get the "phplogin" application working using your personal
database on the class server. You may run the application entirely on
the class server or run the PHP code on your home PC or a lab computer.
Note that the scripts use the older "mysql" set of PHP functions to
communicate with the database.
        
      </li>

      <li>Zip or archive all of the application files into a file named
<span style="font-weight: bold;">p4ex1.zip</span> or
<span style="font-weight: bold;">p4ex1.tar.gz</span> for submission.
      
      </li>
    
    </ol>

  </blockquote>

  
  <h4>Exercise 2</h4>

  <blockquote>
  <ol>

    <li>Modify the PHP code of the "phplogin" application to use the
newer "mysqli" library of functions to access the MySQL database. (Make
sure you have saved the version of the application from Exercise 1
before you begin these modifications!)
      
      </li>

    <li>Get the PHP
application working with the "mysqli" functions.
    </li>
    
    <li>Zip or archive all the application files into a file named
<span style="font-weight: bold;">p4ex2.zip</span> or
<span style="font-weight: bold;">p4ex2.tar.gz</span> for submission.

    </li>

  
  </ol>
  </blockquote>
    <p><span style="font-weight: bold;">Note:</span>
You may, alternatively, create subdirectories (say "ex1" and "ex2")
under your <span style="font-weight: bold;">project4</span> directory
